commit.message:
rtslib: explicitely import "kmod.error" and "kmod.Kmod"

While updating python-kmod to be able to be compiled with Cython 3.0,
I encountered a failure due to rtslib not finding the "error" and "Kmod"
modules.

$ targetcli
module 'kmod' has no attribute 'error'

If I explicitely import those two modules the failure goes away.

Signed-off-by: Maurizio Lombardi <mlombard@redhat.com>

commit.message:
dbroot: let the user change the dbroot directory freely.

Thanks to a new kernel patch, the LIO driver now lets the user change
the dbroot directory even if some target modules are already registered
(if some conditions are met).

rtslib should let the user set their preferred root directory without
arbitrary checks and let the kernel decide if this is allowed or not.

Signed-off-by: Maurizio Lombardi <mlombard@redhat.com>

commit.message:
Filter fabric wwns by reading driver name

symbolic_name [1] is an attribute that represents any human-readable
string that means the name of a node or a port. This string can be
formatted in many different ways:

 - <HBA Model> FW: <Firmware Level> DVR: <Driver Level>
 - <HBA Model> FW: <Firmware Level> DVR: <Driver Level> - <Function>
 - <Manufacturer> <Device Type> <Model>
 - <Port Name>: <Vendor Name>: <Model> [<Device Number>]

Storage vendors can change symbolic_name for their needs to represent
array port name or array name. It is not a persistent way to determine
if a WWN is supported in fabric module. A more reliable way is to check
driver name.

1. https://standards.incits.org/apps/group_public/download.php/82426/T11-2016-046v0.pdf

Signed-off-by: Anastasia Kovaleva <a.kovaleva@yadro.com>

Add support of efct fabric driver

config parameter DataPagesPerBlk alias data_pages_per_blk.

This change enables rtslib to save the new config parameter
to saveconfig.json.

Relax restrictions on TPG Tag range

commit.message:
Relax restrictions on TPG Tag range

Currently rtslib forbids TPG Tag 0. According to
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7143#section-13.9 this is perfectly legal
value, and I've tested it with Linux, Windows, ESXi and AIX initiators.

This commit relaxes the restriction and allows TPG Tag to be 0. I've
kept current behavior in automatic tags assignment so nothing changes
there (e.g. the first TPG will be 1 unless the user explicitly tells
otherwise).

commit.message:
rtslib: Use O_RDWR for sg devices alone.

Using O_RDWR flag for read-only devices will always result in
is_dev_in_use() to return False while sg devices require O_RDWR flag.
Hence, determine this difference programatically and use the flags
appropriately.

Fixes: 964520037320 ("Fix EPERM errors with scsi_generic devices")
Signed-off-by: Sudhakar Panneerselvam <sudhakar.panneerselvam@oracle.com>
